**1. Translation (proper names kept in Chinese)**  

> **Wei Wu‑hou** (魏武侯) was deliberating on affairs and his judgments were correct; none of his ministers could match him. After the court session he withdrew with a pleased expression.  
>   
> **Wu Qi** (吳起) stepped forward and said: “Have you ever heard, from those around you, the words of **King Zhuang of Chu** (楚莊王)?”  
>   
> **Wei Wu‑hou** replied: “What were the words of King Zhuang of Chu?”  
>   
> **Wu Qi** answered:  
>   
> “King Zhuang of Chu deliberated on affairs and his judgments were correct; none of his ministers could match him. After the court session he withdrew with a worried look.  
>   
> **Shen Gong Wu‑chen** (申公巫臣) stepped forward and asked: ‘Your Majesty, why do you appear worried after court?’  
>   
> **King Zhuang of Chu** replied:  
>   
> ‘I, the unworthy one, have deliberated correctly and none of my ministers can match me; therefore I am worried. This is in accordance with the saying of the **Zhong‑lü** (中蘬) – “The feudal lords who obtain a teacher become kings; those who obtain a friend become hegemons; those who obtain doubt survive; those who rely on their own counsel and find no one equal to them perish.’  
>   
> Now, because I am unworthy and yet none of my ministers can equal me, my state is on the verge of ruin. That is why I am worried.’  
>   
> King Zhuang of Chu was worried, whereas you, Lord Wei, are pleased.”  
>   
> **Wei Wu‑hou** bowed twice, stepped back a little, and said: “Heaven has sent you, Master, to point out my fault.”  

---

**2. Moral of the story**

The tale teaches that **self‑satisfaction and pride in one’s own ability are dangerous signs of impending decline**.  

* When a ruler (or any leader) feels pleased because his judgments are unmatched, he is blind to the risk that his superiority may isolate him from useful counsel and breed complacency.  
* The contrasting attitude of King Zhuang of Chu shows true wisdom: even when his decisions are sound, he feels anxiety because he recognizes that reliance on his own unaided judgment (“自為謀而莫己若”) is a harbinger of loss.  
* The moral is therefore: **humility, vigilance, and the willingness to doubt one’s own correctness are essential for lasting success; pride that leads to self‑congratulation invites downfall**.  

In Confucian terms, the story reinforces the virtue of **“敬” (reverence/seriousness)** and the danger of **“驕” (arrogance/pride)**. It echoes the classic Confucian warning that a ruler who does not remain modest and open to criticism will lose the Mandate of Heaven.

---

**3. Counterparts in Western (European) thought**

Yes. The idea that excessive self‑confidence or pride precedes ruin is a recurring theme in Western philosophy, literature, and religion.

| Western concept | How it mirrors the story |
|-----------------|--------------------------|
| **Hubris** (Greek ὕβρις) – excessive pride or defiance of the gods, leading to nemesis (downfall). | King Zhuang’s worry reflects an awareness of hubris; Wei Wu‑hou’s pleasure is the hubristic state that invites nemesis. |
| **Socratic humility** – “I know that I know nothing.” Socrates’ claim that true wisdom lies in recognizing one’s ignorance. | King Zhuang’s anxiety stems from recognizing the limits of his own judgment; Wei Wu‑hou’s pleasure shows a lack of Socratic self‑examination. |
| **Christian humility** – “Pride goes before a fall” (Proverbs 16:18) and the call to be “poor in spirit” (Matthew 5:3). | The story’s moral is virtually identical to the biblical proverb; both warn that self‑exaltation leads to ruin. |
| **Augustine’s doctrine of pride** – pride as the root of sin, the opposite of the virtue of humility. | King Zhuang’s worry is a manifestation of the virtue of humility; Wei Wu‑hou’s pleasure is the sin of pride. |
| **Machiavellian prudence** – a ruler must constantly watch for signs of complacency and maintain the appearance of virtue. | While Machiavelli focuses on power, his advice to stay vigilant against self‑satisfaction parallels King Zhuang’s cautious stance. |
| **Modern psychological concept of the Dunning‑Kruger effect** – individuals with low ability overestimate their competence, while experts often doubt themselves. | King Zhuang’s doubt despite correct judgments mirrors the expert’s self‑critical stance; Wei Wu‑hou’s pleasure mirrors the overconfidence of the less competent. |

Thus, the story’s core lesson finds clear analogues in the Western intellectual tradition: the warning against hubris, the praise of intellectual humility, and the belief that self‑critical vigilance is a safeguard against downfall. [end of text]


